#compdef dkim-keygen
# ============================================================================
# dkim-keygen - generate RSA or Ed25519 DKIM signing keys
#                + emit the matching DNS TXT record
#                (Go, MIT)
#
# Author : Simon Ser (emersion)
# Upstream: https://github.com/emersion/go-msgauth
#           (cmd/dkim-keygen)
#
# `dkim-keygen` is the DKIM-key-pair generator from the
# emersion/go-msgauth toolkit (alongside dkim-milter,
# dkim-verify, and dmarc-lookup). The tool generates a
# fresh RSA-3072 (default) or Ed25519 (with `-t ed25519`)
# private key, writes it as PKCS#8-PEM to disk, and
# prints the corresponding public key formatted as a
# DKIM-compliant DNS TXT record value
# (`v=DKIM1; k=<keyType>; p=<base64-pubkey>`). The output
# is paste-ready into the `<selector>._domainkey` TXT
# record on the signing domain.
#
# Usage:
#   dkim-keygen [-t rsa|ed25519] [-b BITS] [-f FILE] [-y]
#
# Flags (flag.* stdlib parsing):
#   -t <type>           - key type: rsa (default) or
#                          ed25519
#   -b <bits>           - RSA key size in bits (default
#                          3072, ignored for ed25519)
#   -f <file>           - private key filename
#                          (default dkim.priv)
#   -y                  - read existing private key file
#                          + emit its public key TXT
#                          record (no new key generated)
#
# Output format (DKIM v1 TXT record, RFC 6376):
#   v=DKIM1; k=rsa;     p=<base64-SubjectPublicKeyInfo>
#   v=DKIM1; k=ed25519; p=<base64-raw-32-byte-pubkey>
#
# Per RFC 6376 / RFC 8463: RSA pubkeys are encoded as
# SubjectPublicKeyInfo for compat with opendkim + Gmail
# + Fastmail; Ed25519 pubkeys are encoded as the raw
# 32-byte point.
#
# The crypto/ed25519 lane is built on `crypto/ed25519`
# (declared at upstream go.mod via the Go stdlib;
# imported from cmd/dkim-keygen/main.go as `crypto/
# ed25519`), the canonical Go Ed25519 implementation by
# the Go core team. Originally introduced in the
# `golang.org/x/crypto/ed25519` subrepository, the
# package was promoted to the std-lib `crypto/ed25519`
# in Go 1.13 (released 2019). The package re-exports the
# x/crypto/ed25519 implementation byte-for-byte; either
# import path gives the same library.
#
# The implementation tracks RFC 8032 (Edwards-curve
# Digital Signature Algorithm) end-to-end + tracks the
# FIPS 186-5 update that brought Ed25519 into the NIST
# digital-signature standard. Constant-time operations,
# pure-Go (no FFI), and the standard library's stable
# API guarantee make it the Go-ecosystem default Ed25519
# library.
#
# dkim-keygen uses `ed25519.GenerateKey(rand.Reader)` to
# produce the (public, private) pair when `-t ed25519`
# is selected, then marshals the private key as PKCS#8
# via `x509.MarshalPKCS8PrivateKey` (which accepts the
# `ed25519.PrivateKey` type natively since Go 1.13). The
# public key is emitted raw (per RFC 8463 §3.1: "the
# public key data is the raw 32-byte Ed25519 public key
# encoded as base64").
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 246 :: Ed25519 / EdDSA signatures (RFC 8032)
# Round 1437 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 246
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : dalek-cryptography/ed25519-dalek
#                                       [R1436 _atm0s-reverse-proxy-agent]
#   Go      : crypto/ed25519 (std-lib;  [R1437 THIS FILE]
#             same impl as
#             golang.org/x/crypto/ed25519)
#   TS/Node : paulmillr/noble-ed25519   [R1438 closing]
#             (npm @noble/ed25519)
#
# crypto/ed25519 is structurally interesting in this
# axis because of its *single-implementation across-two-
# import-paths* pattern. The Go core team originally
# shipped `golang.org/x/crypto/ed25519` (in the x/* sub-
# repository) before Ed25519 was a widely-deployed
# algorithm. As Ed25519 adoption matured (mid-2010s),
# the implementation was promoted to the std-lib at
# `crypto/ed25519` in Go 1.13 (Sep 2019), with the
# x/crypto package becoming a re-export alias that
# preserves source-level compat with code written before
# the std-lib version existed.
#
# This promotion pattern is unique to the Go ecosystem
# in this axis cluster. The Rust slot's ed25519-dalek
# crate stays in the broader dalek-cryptography umbrella
# and is never absorbed into a std-lib equivalent (Rust's
# stdlib does not provide cryptographic primitives by
# design). The Node slot's @noble/ed25519 stays an
# independent npm package with no std-lib presence.
#
# Structural commentary on the std-lib promotion:
#   - Pre-Go 1.13: code used `golang.org/x/crypto/
#     ed25519.GenerateKey` etc.
#   - Post-Go 1.13: code uses `crypto/ed25519.
#     GenerateKey` etc. - same function, same bytes,
#     different import path
#   - The x/crypto/ed25519 package is now an alias to
#     the std-lib version, so legacy code keeps working
#     unchanged
#
# dkim-keygen chose the std-lib `crypto/ed25519` path
# because it's the Go 1.13+ idiomatic import - the
# x/crypto/ed25519 alias exists for back-compat but new
# code should target the std-lib.
#
# Cross-language interop at the wire format level: a
# 64-byte Ed25519 signature produced by ed25519-dalek +
# crypto/ed25519 + @noble/ed25519 is byte-identical for
# the same (private_key, message) pair, modulo encoding
# of the public key (raw 32-byte vs SubjectPublicKeyInfo
# vs PKCS#8 - DKIM uses raw 32-byte per RFC 8463).
# ============================================================================

_dkim-keygen() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '-t[key type]:type:(rsa ed25519)' \
        '-b[RSA key size in bits (ignored for ed25519)]:bits:' \
        '-f[private key filename]:file:_files' \
        '-y[read existing private key + emit public TXT record]' \
        '(- *)-h[print help]'
}

_dkim-keygen "$@"
